      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "HiC-Pro proposes a fast sparse-based implementation of the iterative correction method [17], allowing normalization of genome-wide high-resolution contact matrices in a short time and with reasonable memory requirements.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms HiC-Pro uses iterative correction (ICE) for normalization, but states the implementation is BUILT INTO HiC-Pro itself, not a separate iced module installation. Paper says 'The code for the normalization is available as a standalone package (https://github.com/hiclib/iced) as well as being included in HiC-Pro.' This indicates iced is optional/standalone, not a required separate install for HiC-Pro normalization. The card frames this as a required external dependency that 'no longer ships with HiC-Pro source code,' but the paper (2015) describes iced as already integrated.",
